that it can contain the four other

267
00:11:06,820 --> 00:11:08,820
top industrialized nations' economies

268
00:11:08,820 --> 00:11:11,820
inside itself, it's so vastly rich.

269
00:11:11,820 --> 00:11:14,820
So its military budget is bound to be enormous.

270
00:11:14,820 --> 00:11:16,820
So, to be fair and to alter our perspective,

271
00:11:16,820 --> 00:11:18,820
we have to bring in another data set,

272
00:11:18,820 --> 00:11:20,820
and that data set is GDP, or the country's earnings.

273
00:11:20,820 --> 00:11:22,820
Who has the biggest budget as a proportion of GDP?

274
00:11:22,820 --> 00:11:24,820
Let's have a look.

275
00:11:24,820 --> 00:11:27,820
That changes the picture considerably.

276
00:11:27,820 --> 00:11:30,820
Other countries pop into view that you, perhaps, weren't considering,

277
00:11:30,820 --> 00:11:32,820
and American drops into eighth.

278
00:11:32,820 --> 00:11:34,820
Now you can also do this with soldiers.

279
00:11:34,820 --> 00:11:36,820
Who has the most soldiers? It's got to be China.

280
00:11:36,820 --> 00:11:38,820
Of course, 2.1 million.

281
00:11:38,820 --> 00:11:40,820
Again, chiming with your view

282
00:11:40,820 --> 00:11:42,820
that China has a militarized regime

283
00:11:42,820 --> 00:11:44,820
ready to, you know, mobilize its enormous forces.

284
00:11:44,820 --> 00:11:47,820
But of course, China has an enormous population.

285
00:11:47,820 --> 00:11:49,820
So if we do the same,

286
00:11:49,820 --> 00:11:51,820
we see a radically different picture.

287
00:11:51,820 --> 00:11:53,820
China drops to 124th.

288
00:11:53,820 --> 00:11:55,820
It actually has a tiny army

289
00:11:55,820 --> 00:11:58,820
when you take other data into consideration.

290
00:11:58,820 --> 00:12:00,820
So, absolute figures, like the military budget,

291
00:12:00,820 --> 00:12:02,820
in a connected world,

292
00:12:02,820 --> 00:12:04,820
don't give you the whole picture.

293
00:12:04,820 --> 00:12:06,820
They're not as true as they could be.

294
00:12:06,820 --> 00:12:09,820
We need relative figures that are connected to other data

295
00:12:09,820 --> 00:12:11,820
so that we can see a fuller picture,

296
00:12:11,820 --> 00:12:13,820
and then that can lead to us changing our perspective.

297
00:12:13,820 --> 00:12:15,820
As Hans Rosling, the master,

298
00:12:15,820 --> 00:12:18,820
my master, said,

299
00:12:18,820 --> 00:12:21,820
"Let the dataset change your mindset."

300
00:12:22,820 --> 00:12:25,820
And if it can do that, maybe it can also change your behavior.

301
00:12:25,820 --> 00:12:27,820
Take a look at this one.

302
00:12:27,820 --> 00:12:29,820
I'm a bit of a health nut.

303
00:12:29,820 --> 00:12:32,820
I love taking supplements and being fit,

304
00:12:32,820 --> 00:12:35,820
but I can never understand what's going on in terms of evidence.

305
00:12:35,820 --> 00:12:37,820
There's always conflicting evidence.

306
00:12:37,820 --> 00:12:39,820
Should I take vitamin C? Should I be taking wheatgrass?

307
00:12:39,820 --> 00:12:41,820
This is a visualization of all the evidence

308
00:12:41,820 --> 00:12:43,820
for nutritional supplements.

309
00:12:43,820 --> 00:12:46,820
This kind of diagram is called a balloon race.

310
00:12:46,820 --> 00:12:48,820
So the higher up the image,

311
00:12:48,820 --> 00:12:51,820
the more evidence there is for each supplement.

312
00:12:51,820 --> 00:12:54,820
And the bubbles correspond to popularity as regards to Google hits.

313
00:12:54,820 --> 00:12:57,820
So you can immediately apprehend

314
00:12:57,820 --> 00:13:00,820
the relationship between efficacy and popularity,

315
00:13:00,820 --> 00:13:03,820
but you can also, if you grade the evidence,

316
00:13:03,820 --> 00:13:05,820
do a "worth it" line.

317
00:13:05,820 --> 00:13:08,820
So supplements above this line are worth investigating,

318
00:13:08,820 --> 00:13:11,820
but only for the conditions listed below,

319
00:13:11,820 --> 00:13:14,820
and then the supplements below the line

320
00:13:14,820 --> 00:13:16,820
are perhaps not worth investigating.

321
00:13:16,820 --> 00:13:19,820
Now this image constitutes a huge amount of work.

322
00:13:19,820 --> 00:13:22,820
We scraped like 1,000 studies from PubMed,

323
00:13:22,820 --> 00:13:24,820
the biomedical database,

324
00:13:24,820 --> 00:13:27,820
and we compiled them and graded them all.

325
00:13:27,820 --> 00:13:29,820
And it was incredibly frustrating for me

326
00:13:29,820 --> 00:13:32,820
because I had a book of 250 visualizations to do for my book,

327
00:13:32,820 --> 00:13:34,820
and I spent a month doing this,

328
00:13:34,820 --> 00:13:36,820
and I only filled two pages.

329
00:13:36,820 --> 00:13:38,820
But what it points to

330
00:13:38,820 --> 00:13:40,820
is that visualizing information like this

331
00:13:40,820 --> 00:13:42,820
is a form of knowledge compression.

332
00:13:42,820 --> 00:13:44,820
It's a way of squeezing an enormous amount

333
00:13:44,820 --> 00:13:46,820
of information and understanding

334
00:13:46,820 --> 00:13:48,820
into a small space.

335
00:13:48,820 --> 00:13:50,820
And once you've curated that data, and once you've cleaned that data,

336
00:13:50,820 --> 00:13:52,820
and once it's there,

337
00:13:52,820 --> 00:13:54,820
you can do cool stuff like this.

338
00:13:54,820 --> 00:13:56,820
So I converted this into an interactive app,

339
00:13:56,820 --> 00:13:58,820
so I can now generate this application online --

340
00:13:58,820 --> 00:14:00,820
this is the visualization online --

341
00:14:00,820 --> 00:14:02,820
and I can say, "Yeah, brilliant."

342
00:14:02,820 --> 00:14:04,820
So it spawns itself.

343
00:14:04,820 --> 00:14:06,820
And then I can say, "Well, just show me the stuff

344
00:14:06,820 --> 00:14:08,820
that affects heart health."

345
00:14:08,820 --> 00:14:10,820
So let's filter that out.

346
00:14:10,820 --> 00:14:13,820
So heart is filtered out, so I can see if I'm curious about that.

347
00:14:13,820 --> 00:14:15,820
I think, "No, no. I don't want to take any synthetics,

348
00:14:15,820 --> 00:14:18,820
I just want to see plants and --

349
00:14:18,820 --> 00:14:21,820
just show me herbs and plants. I've got all the natural ingredients."

350
00:14:21,820 --> 00:14:23,820
Now this app is spawning itself

351
00:14:23,820 --> 00:14:25,820
from the data.

352
00:14:25,820 --> 00:14:27,820
The data is all stored in a Google Doc,

353
00:14:27,820 --> 00:14:30,820
and it's literally generating itself from that data.

354
00:14:30,820 --> 00:14:32,820
So the data is now alive; this is a living image,

355
00:14:32,820 --> 00:14:34,820
and I can update it in a second.

356
00:14:34,820 --> 00:14:36,820
New evidence comes out. I just change a row on a spreadsheet.

357
00:14:36,820 --> 00:14:40,820
Doosh! Again, the image recreates itself.

358
00:14:40,820 --> 00:14:42,820
So it's cool.

359
00:14:42,820 --> 00:14:45,820
It's kind of living.

360
00:14:45,820 --> 00:14:47,820
But it can go beyond data,

361
00:14:47,820 --> 00:14:49,820
and it can go beyond numbers.

362
00:14:49,820 --> 00:14:51,820
I like to apply information visualization

363
00:14:51,820 --> 00:14:54,820
to ideas and concepts.

364
00:14:54,820 --> 00:14:56,820
This is a visualization

365
00:14:56,820 --> 00:14:58,820
of the political spectrum,

366
00:14:58,820 --> 00:15:00,820
an attempt for me to try

367
00:15:00,820 --> 00:15:02,820
and understand how it works

368
00:15:02,820 --> 00:15:04,820
and how the ideas percolate down

369
00:15:04,820 --> 00:15:06,820
from government into society and culture,

370
00:15:06,820 --> 00:15:09,820
into families, into individuals, into their beliefs

371
00:15:09,820 --> 00:15:12,820
and back around again in a cycle.

372
00:15:12,820 --> 00:15:14,820
What I love about this image

373
00:15:14,820 --> 00:15:16,820
is it's made up of concepts,

374
00:15:16,820 --> 00:15:18,820
it explores our worldviews

375
00:15:18,820 --> 00:15:20,820
and it helps us -- it helps me anyway --

376
00:15:20,820 --> 00:15:22,820
to see what others think,

377
00:15:22,820 --> 00:15:24,820
to see where they're coming from.

378
00:15:24,820 --> 00:15:27,820
And it feels just incredibly cool to do that.

379
00:15:27,820 --> 00:15:30,820
What was most exciting for me

380
00:15:30,820 --> 00:15:32,820
designing this

381
00:15:32,820 --> 00:15:34,820
was that, when I was designing this image,

382
00:15:34,820 --> 00:15:37,820
I desperately wanted this side, the left side,

383
00:15:37,820 --> 00:15:39,820
to be better than the right side --

384
00:15:39,820 --> 00:15:42,820
being a journalist, a Left-leaning person --

385
00:15:42,820 --> 00:15:44,820
but I couldn't, because I would have created

386
00:15:44,820 --> 00:15:47,820
a lopsided, biased diagram.

387
00:15:47,820 --> 00:15:50,820
So, in order to really create a full image,

388
00:15:50,820 --> 00:15:53,820
I had to honor the perspectives on the right-hand side

389
00:15:53,820 --> 00:15:56,820
and at the same time, uncomfortably recognize

390
00:15:56,820 --> 00:15:59,820
how many of those qualities were actually in me,

391
00:15:59,820 --> 00:16:01,820
which was very, very annoying and uncomfortable.

392
00:16:01,820 --> 00:16:05,820
(Laughter)

393
00:16:05,820 --> 00:16:07,820
But not too uncomfortable,

394
00:16:07,820 --> 00:16:10,820
because there's something unthreatening

395
00:16:10,820 --> 00:16:12,820
about seeing a political perspective,

396
00:16:12,820 --> 00:16:15,820
versus being told or forced to listen to one.

397
00:16:15,820 --> 00:16:18,820
You're capable of holding conflicting viewpoints

398
00:16:18,820 --> 00:16:20,820
joyously when you can see them.

399
00:16:20,820 --> 00:16:22,820
It's even fun to engage with them

400
00:16:22,820 --> 00:16:24,820
because it's visual.

401
00:16:24,820 --> 00:16:26,820
So that's what's exciting to me,

402
00:16:26,820 --> 00:16:28,820
seeing how data can change my perspective

403
00:16:28,820 --> 00:16:30,820
and change my mind midstream --

404
00:16:30,820 --> 00:16:33,820
beautiful, lovely data.

405
00:16:34,820 --> 00:16:36,820
So, just to wrap up,

406
00:16:36,820 --> 00:16:38,820
I wanted to say

407
00:16:38,820 --> 00:16:40,820
that it feels to me that design is about solving problems

408
00:16:40,820 --> 00:16:43,820
and providing elegant solutions,

409
00:16:43,820 --> 00:16:45,820
and information design is about

410
00:16:45,820 --> 00:16:47,820
solving information problems.

411
00:16:47,820 --> 00:16:49,820
It feels like we have a lot of information problems

412
00:16:49,820 --> 00:16:51,820
in our society at the moment,

413
00:16:51,820 --> 00:16:53,820
from the overload and the saturation

414
00:16:53,820 --> 00:16:55,820
to the breakdown of trust and reliability

415
00:16:55,820 --> 00:16:57,820
and runaway skepticism and lack of transparency,

416
00:16:57,820 --> 00:16:59,820
or even just interestingness.

417
00:16:59,820 --> 00:17:01,820
I mean, I find information just too interesting.

418
00:17:01,820 --> 00:17:04,820
It has a magnetic quality that draws me in.

419
00:17:05,820 --> 00:17:07,820
So, visualizing information

420
00:17:07,820 --> 00:17:10,820
can give us a very quick solution to those kinds of problems.

421
00:17:10,820 --> 00:17:12,820
Even when the information is terrible,

422
00:17:12,820 --> 00:17:15,820
the visual can be quite beautiful.

423
00:17:15,820 --> 00:17:18,820
Often we can get clarity

424
00:17:18,820 --> 00:17:20,820
or the answer to a simple question very quickly,

425
00:17:20,820 --> 00:17:22,820
like this one,

426
00:17:22,820 --> 00:17:25,820
the recent Icelandic volcano.

427
00:17:25,820 --> 00:17:27,820
Which was emitting the most CO2?

428
00:17:27,820 --> 00:17:29,820
Was it the planes or the volcano,

429
00:17:29,820 --> 00:17:31,820
the grounded planes or the volcano?

430
00:17:31,820 --> 00:17:33,820
So we can have a look.

431
00:17:33,820 --> 00:17:35,820
We look at the data and we see:

432
00:17:35,820 --> 00:17:37,820
Yep, the volcano emitted 150,000 tons;

433
00:17:37,820 --> 00:17:39,820
the grounded planes would have emitted

434
00:17:39,820 --> 00:17:42,820
345,000 if they were in the sky.

435
00:17:42,820 --> 00:17:45,820
So essentially, we had our first carbon-neutral volcano.

436
00:17:45,820 --> 00:17:47,820
(Laughter)

437
00:17:47,820 --> 00:17:56,820
(Applause)

438
00:17:56,820 --> 00:17:59,820
And that is beautiful. Thank you.

439
00:17:59,820 --> 00:18:07,820
(Applause)

